## Step 1 — Understand why port mapping exists
  A container has its own private network namespace, meaning:
      • It has its own IP (like 172.17.0.2)
      • It has its own ports (like 80, 5000, 8080)
      • These ports are not reachable from your host unless you explicitly expose them.
  So Docker gives us a mechanism:
      HostPort : ContainerPort
  
  This tells Docker:
    “When traffic comes to HostPort, forward it to ContainerPort inside the container.”



## Step 2 — Run a container with port mapping
  To run a container with port mapping, you can use the -p flag with the docker run command. The syntax is:
      docker run -p HostPort:ContainerPort ImageName 
  For example, if you have a web application running on port 80 inside the container and you want to access it on port 8080 on your host, you would run:
      docker run -p 8080:80 ImageName
  This command tells Docker to forward traffic from port 8080 on your host to port 80 inside the container, allowing you to access the web application by navigating to http://localhost:8080 in your web browser.


## Step 3 — Verify the port mapping
  After running the container with port mapping, you can verify that the ports are correctly mapped by using the docker ps command to list the running containers and their port mappings. You should see an entry similar to:
      CONTAINER ID   IMAGE         COMMAND                  CREATED          STATUS          PORTS                    NAMES
      abc123         ImageName     "your_command_here"      10 seconds ago   Up 10 seconds   0.0.0.0:8080->80/tcp     mycontainer 
  This indicates that port 8080 on the host is mapped to port 80 in the container, confirming that the port mapping is set up correctly. You can now access your application through the specified host port.


## Step 4 — Access the application
  With the port mapping in place, you can access the application running inside the container by navigating to http://localhost:HostPort in your web browser. 
  For example, if you mapped port 8080 on your host to port 80 in the container, you would go to http://localhost:8080 to access the application. This allows you to interact with the application as if it were running directly on your host machine, while it is actually running inside the isolated environment of the Docker container.

## Step 5 — Clean up
  After you are done testing or using the application, you can stop and remove the container to free up resources. You can use the following commands:
      docker stop ContainerID
      docker rm ContainerID
  Replace ContainerID with the actual ID of your running container, which you can find using the
      docker ps
  command. Stopping the container will halt its execution, and removing it will delete the container from your system, allowing you to start fresh with new containers as needed.

## Conclusion
  Port mapping is a crucial aspect of working with Docker containers, 
  as it allows you to expose services running inside the container to the outside world. 
  By understanding how to set up and verify port mappings, you can effectively manage and access your applications running in Docker containers, 
  making it easier to develop, test, and deploy your applications in a consistent and isolated environment.


## The mental model of port mapping 
  - The container is like a small ship with its own private network and ports. 
  - The host machine is like a port where the ship docks. 
  - Port mapping is like assigning a specific dock (HostPort) for the ship to unload its cargo (ContainerPort). 
  - When you want to access the cargo, you go to the assigned dock on the host machine, and it will be forwarded to the correct port inside the container where the application is running. 
  - This allows you to interact with the application running inside the container as if it were running directly on your host machine, while still maintaining the isolation and benefits of using Docker containers.

   I want you to visualize this like a pipeline:
      
      Your Browser → Host Machine Port → Docker NAT → Container Port → App

      This pipeline illustrates how a request from your browser goes through the host machine's port, is forwarded by Docker's Network Address Translation (NAT) to the container's port, and finally reaches the application running inside the container. This visualization helps to understand the flow of traffic and how port mapping enables communication between the host and the container.

      So when you write:
          docker run -p 8080:80 ImageName

          You’re telling Docker:
             “Listen on 8080 on the host”
             “Forward that traffic to 80 inside the container”
          This is the core of port mapping.

          docker run -p 5000:80 nginx
          In this example, you are telling Docker to listen on port 5000 on the host machine and forward that traffic to port 80 inside the container where the Nginx web server is running. This allows you to access the Nginx server by navigating to http://localhost:5000 in your web browser, while the actual server is running inside the Docker container on port 80.

## Difference between -p and --expose 

    `--expose`
      • Only documents that the container listens on a port
      • Does not publish the port to the host
      • Only useful for Docker networks (container-to-container communication)
    
    `-p` or `--publish`
      • Actually binds a host port
      • Makes the container reachable from outside
      • Creates NAT rules
      
      So, 
          docker run --expose 80 nginx
          → You cannot access it from browser.

      But, 
          docker run -p 8080:80 nginx
          → You can access it from browser at http://localhost:8080.


## The three types of port publishing in Docker
    Most people only know -p, but Docker actually supports three different modes of publishing ports.
    Let’s explore them one by one.

    1) -p HOST:CONTAINER` — Manual port mapping (you choose the host port)
    
        Example: docker run -p 8080:80 nginx

    2) -p CONTAINER` — Automatic port mapping (Docker chooses the host port)
        Example: docker run -p 80 nginx
        In this case, Docker will automatically assign a random available port on the host machine and map it to port 80 in the container. You can find out which port was assigned by using the docker ps command after the container is running.  

        This is useful when:
        • You don’t care which host port is used
        • You want to run many containers without conflicts
        • You want Docker to manage port allocation
      
      You can check the assigned port using:  
            docker ps 

    3) 3️⃣ `--network host` — No port mapping at all

        This is advanced and only works on Linux.
        
        If you run:

            docker run --network host nginx

        Then:
          • The container shares the host’s network stack
          • No NAT
          • No port mapping
          • Nginx listens directly on host port 80
          This is extremely fast but removes network isolation.


  
