      1. Create a simple web application:
          - You can create a simple HTML file named index.html with the following content:
              ```html
              <!DOCTYPE html>
              <html>
              <head>
                  <title>My Docker App</title>
              </head>
              <body>
                  <h1>Hello, Docker!</h1>
              </body>
              </html>
              ```
          - Save this file in a directory on your local machine.  
      2. Build a Docker image for the application:
          - Create a Dockerfile in the same directory with the following content:
              ```Dockerfile
              # Use an official Nginx image as the base image
              FROM nginx:alpine 
              # Copy the index.html file to the Nginx HTML directory
              COPY index.html /usr/share/nginx/html/index.html
              ```
          - Open a terminal, navigate to the directory containing the Dockerfile and index.html, and run the following command to build the Docker image:
              ```bash
              docker build -t my-docker-app .
              ```
          - This command tells Docker to build an image with the tag "my-docker-app" using the Dockerfile in the current directory (indicated by the dot).
      3. Run the container with port mapping:
          - After the image is built, you can run a container from the image with port mapping using the following command:
              ```bash
              docker run -d -p 8080:80 --name my-docker-container my-docker-app
              ```
          - This command runs the container in detached mode (-d), maps port 8080 on the host to port 80 in the container, and names the container "my-docker-container".
      4. Access the application:
          - Open your web browser and navigate to http://localhost:8080. You should see the message "Hello, Docker!" displayed on the page, indicating that the application is running correctly inside the Docker container and is accessible through the mapped port on your host machine.
      5. Clean up:
          - To stop the running container, use the following command:
              ```bash
              docker stop my-docker-container
              ```
          - To remove the container from your system, use the following command:
              ```bash
              docker rm my-docker-container
              ```
          - This will stop the container and then remove it, allowing you to free up resources and keep your environment clean for future use. You can also remove the Docker image if you no longer need it using the following command:
              ```bash
              docker rmi my-docker-app
              ```
          - This command will remove the Docker image from your system, ensuring that you have a clean slate for future projects.

